{{refimprove|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox scientist |name = Antonín Frič |image = Fric Antonin.jpg |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = June 30, 1832 |birth_place = [[Prague]] |death_date = November 15, 1913 |death_place = Prague |residence = |citizenship = |nationality = [[Czechoslovakia|Czech]] |ethnicity = |fields = [[paleontology]] |workplaces = [[Charles University]], [[National Museum (Prague)|National Museum in Prague]] |alma_mater = |doctoral_advisor = |academic_advisors = |doctoral_students = |notable_students = |known_for = contributions on the field of [[permian|permo]]-[[carboniferous]] [[ecosystem]]s |author_abbrev_bot = |author_abbrev_zoo = |influences = |influenced = |awards = |religion = |signature = <!--(filename only)--> |footnotes = }} '''Antonín Jan Frič''' (in German: Anton Johann Fritsch, June 30, 1832 – November 15, 1913) was a [[Czechs|Czech]] [[paleontologist]], [[biologist]] and [[geologist]], living during the [[Austria–Hungary]] era. Professor at the [[Charles University]] and later became director of the [[National Museum (Prague)|National Museum in Prague]]. He became famous for his contributions on the field of [[Permian|Permo]] - [[Carboniferous]] [[ecosystem]]s.
He also became known for finding fossils once attributed to [[dinosaur]]s - ''[[Albisaurus]] albinus'' and ''[[Ponerosteus]] exogyrarum'' and so far the only [[pterosaur]] known from the Czech Republic, ''[[Cretornis hlavaci]]''. The [[pterosaur]] was small with a wingspan of about 1.5 m and lived in the [[Turonian]].
The first true dinosaur known from the Czech Republic was discovered 90 years after Frič's death (in 2003). It is a small ornithopod of Cenomanian age.<ref>http://app.pan.pl/archive/published/app50/app50-295.pdf</ref>
Fritsch received the [[Lyell Medal]] from the [[Geological Society of London]] in 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Geological Society of London|day_of_week=Monday |date=24 February 1902 |page_number=6 |issue=36699| }}</ref>
