{{Infobox scientist | name = Nicholas Ingolia | birth_name = Nicholas Thomas Ingolia | birth_date = {{bda|1979|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Nicholas Thomas Ingolia, Born 02/05/1979 in California |url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/nicholas_thomas_ingolia_born_1979_14062607 |website=California Birth Index |accessdate=August 5, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> | birth_place = [[San Francisco]], [[California]] | image =}}
'''Nicholas Thomas Ingolia''' (born February 5, 1979) is an American [[molecular biology|molecular biologist]] and assistant professor at [[University of California, Berkeley]]. He is most known for the development of the method of [[ribosome profiling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingolia-lab.org/ingolia-cv.pdf|title=Nicholas Ingolia CV|access-date=2018-02-21|website=ingolia-lab.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcb.berkeley.edu/faculty/bbs/ingolian.html|title=Faculty Research Page: Nicholas Ingolia|website=[[University of California, Berkeley]]|date=2013-09-19|access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref> He has also studied the evolution of heat-sensing nerves in [[vampire bat]]s and the encoding of small [[peptide]]s by brief [[open reading frame]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2011/08/110803-vampire-bats-blood-heat-veins-science-animals-nature/|title=Vampire Bats Have Vein Sensors|last=Dell'Amore|first=Christine|date=2011-08-04|work=[[National Geographic]]|access-date=2018-02-21|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/46150/title/Noncoding-RNAs-Not-So-Noncoding/|title=Noncoding RNAs Not So Noncoding|last=Williams|first=Ruth|date=2016-06-01|website=[[The Scientist (magazine)|The Scientist]]|access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref> Ingolia is a 2011 [[Searle Scholars Program|Searle Scholar]] and serves on a peer-review committee for the [[American Cancer Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.searlescholars.net/person/567|title=Searle Scholars Program : Nicholas Ingolia (2011)|website=searlescholars.net|access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cancer.org/research/we-fund-cancer-research/apply-research-grant/peer-review-committees/rna-mechanisms-cancer.html|title=Peer Review Committee for RNA Mechanisms in Cancer (RMC)|website=cancer.org|access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref>
