{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Noriaki Fukuyama | honorific_suffix = | native_name = 福山伯明 | native_name_lang = Japanese | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = 1912 | birth_place = | death_date = 1946 | death_place = [[Taiwan]] | death_cause = murdered | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = Taiwan | citizenship = | nationality = Japanese | fields = Botany | workplaces = Taihoku High School | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = Taihoku Imperial University | thesis_title = <!--(or | thesis1_title = and | thesis2_title = )--> | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = <!--(or | thesis1_year = and | thesis2_year = )--> | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = [[Genkei Masamune]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = Study of South East Asian Orchids | influences = | influenced = | awards = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = <!--(or | spouses = )--> | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} {{nihongo|'''Noriaki Fukuyama'''|福山 伯明|Fukuyama Noriaki|extra=1912 – 1946}} was a Japanese botanist and orchidologist. He died in [[Taiwan]]<ref name=ntuh>{{ cite web |url=http://culture.teldap.tw/culture/index.php?option=com_content&id=871 |title=Kanagawa Prefectural Museum of Natural History |work=Digital Archives Project |publisher=[[National Taiwan University]] Herbarium |accessdate=September 6, 2014}}</ref>
During his short life, Dr. Fukuyama described over a hundred new species of [[orchid]]s from [[Micronesia]], the [[Ryukyu Islands|Ryukyus]] and Taiwan. Most of the type specimens he collected were housed in his personal [[herbarium]] (Herb. Orch. Fuk.), located in Taiwan, and were previously believed to have been lost amid the upheaval in [[Japan]] following the close of [[World War II]]. However, most of Fukuyama's type materials of Taiwan orchids were rediscovered, in the course of sifting through the botanical collection of one [[Genkei Masamune|Dr. Genkei Masamune]], which Masamune had bequeathed to the herbarium of the [[Kanagawa Prefectural Museum of Natural History]] upon his death in 1993. Although it is not entirely clear as to why he had them, it is known that Fukuyama had been Masamune's pupil.<ref name=ntuh/>
Among the materials found were Fukuyama's original manuscripts of ''Studia Orchidacearum Japonicarum'', Vols. XI thru XIII.<ref name=ntuh/>
Suffering from cancer, and plagued by local unrest in Taiwan against the Japanese, he was killed by locals in a nearby village during a local uprising against Japanese citizens living in Taiwan.
